{"altmetric_id":13357518,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":1,"citeulike":0,"connotea":0},"total":{"posts_count":17},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":13,"unique_users":["DrJonathanK","cory_criss","SECIPE","jpedsurg","IllingworthInfo","brunomtzleo","surg4kidslondon","drdanmd","feralvarezlo","AfifKulaylat","nasr_isam","ParraJanepamd","Geralcarol27G"],"posts_count":14},"facebook":{"unique_users_count":3,"unique_users":["177656929270664","401955196539850","130341520339294"],"posts_count":3}},"selected_quotes":["Revisi\u00f3n sistem\u00e1tica del manejo #quirurgico del #reflujo #gastroesof\u00e1gico en ni\u00f1os,","Surgical management of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) in children\u2026 #eprompt #pedsurg"],"citation":{"abstract":"The goal of this systematic review by the American Pediatric Surgical Association Outcomes and Evidence-Based Practice Committee was to derive recommendations from the medical literature regarding the surgical treatment of pediatric gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD).\nFive questions were addressed by searching the MEDLINE, Cochrane, Embase, Central, and National Guideline Clearinghouse databases using relevant search terms. Consensus recommendations were derived for each question based on the best available evidence.\nThere was insufficient evidence to formulate recommendations for all questions. Fundoplication does not affect the rate of hospitalization for aspiration pneumonia, apnea, or reflux-related symptoms. Fundoplication is effective in reducing all parameters of esophageal acid exposure without altering esophageal motility. Laparoscopic fundoplication may be comparable to open fundoplication with regard to short-term clinical outcomes. Partial fundoplication and complete fundoplication are comparable in effectiveness for subjective control of GERD. Fundoplication may benefit GERD patients with asthma, but may not improve outcomes in patients with neurologic impairment or esophageal atresia. Overall GERD recurrence rates are likely below 20%.\nHigh-quality evidence is lacking regarding the surgical management of GERD in the pediatric population. Definitive conclusions regarding the effectiveness of fundoplication are limited by patient heterogeneity and lack of a standardized outcomes reporting framework.\nSystematic review of level 1-4 studies.\nLevel 1-4 (mainly level 3-4).","altmetric_jid":"4f6fa6293cf058f610007dd6","authors":["Tim Jancelewicz","Monica E. Lopez","Cynthia D. Downard","Saleem Islam","Robert Baird","Shawn J. Rangel","Regan F Williams","Meghan A. Arnold","Dave Lal","Elizabeth Renaud","Julia Grabowski","Roshi Dasgupta","Mary Austin","Julia Shelton","Danielle Cameron","Adam B. Goldin","Jancelewicz, Tim","Lopez, Monica E","Downard, Cynthia D","Islam, Saleem","Baird, Robert","Rangel, Shawn J","Williams, Regan F","Arnold, Meghan A","Lal, Dave","Renaud, Elizabeth","Grabowski, Julia","Dasgupta, Roshi","Austin, Mary","Shelton, Julia","Cameron, Danielle","Goldin, Adam B","Roshni Dasgupta","Regan F. Williams"],"doi":"10.1016\/j.jpedsurg.2016.09.072","first_seen_on":"2016-11-05T11:37:15+00:00","funders":["niehs"],"issns":["00223468","1531-5037"],"journal":"Journal of Pediatric Surgery (Science Direct)","last_mentioned_on":1502929699,"links":["http:\/\/www.jpedsurg.org\/article\/S0022-3468(16)30460-2\/fulltext?rss=yes","http:\/\/www.jpedsurg.org\/article\/S0022-3468%2816%2930460-2\/fulltext?elsca1=etoc&amp%3Belsca2=email&amp%3Belsca3=0022-3468_201708_52_8_&amp%3Belsca4=Pediatric+Surgery%7CGeneral+Surgery#.WXar7vw1Mrc.twitter"],"pdf_url":"http:\/\/www.jpedsurg.org\/article\/S0022346816304602\/pdf","pmid":"27823773","pubdate":"2016-10-01T00:00:00+00:00","publisher":"Elsevier","publisher_subjects":[{"name":"Paediatrics And Reproductive Medicine","scheme":"era"}],"scopus_subjects":["Medicine","Health Sciences"],"subjects":["generalsurgery","pediatrics"],"title":"Surgical management of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) in children: A systematic review","type":"article","uri":"http:\/\/